condition_notes: Large amount of debris at the inlet.
climate_notes: This stream appears to be mostly just a runoff and high flow event drainage. Seems unlikely that large quantities of water come through here as the channel is so small and poorly defined.
priority_notes: Very unlikely that this is a fish bearing stream and seems like the risk to the road is low.

condition_notes: Debris catcher on the inlet is separating from the pipe and is jammed up with debris. Plastic pipe appears recently installed.
climate_notes: Only access road to several residences. Very little amount of Phil indicates that with high volume of precipitation the road would wash out.
priority_notes: No fisheries information available but very close to the Kispiox mainstem. Modelled crossing mapped as located downstream on private land but could not be accessed.

condition_notes: Right pipe completely blocked. Structure appears near the end of life. Although ineffective, historic work done downstream to try to backwater the structure.
climate_notes: Large tributary so significant flood eventscould wash out the Date Creek FSR.
priority_notes: Some residences on this road so potentially joint MoTi and MoF management.  Deep fill will make replacement difficult, costs high and blow out consequences significant.

condition_notes: Large amount of flow is going in between the two pipes and not through them. Trash guards on inlets are quite damaged. Beaverdams located immediately down stream. Roadfill material is made of road barriers. Pipes are in bad shape.
climate_notes: Significant amounts of water moving through here and this highway is a major corridor for people living in the Kispiox community and associated valley upstream.
The stream does not appear to flow very much as it was surveyed in a very wet. And there is no flow at this time.

condition_notes: Culvert is separated in areas and slumping
A lot of mud and debris in culvert

1 m high Beaverdam immediately upstream in the inlet. Left pipe has extension on it going underneath the Beaverdam. Inlet appears to have been recently dug out to three blockage issues. There is a old piece of culvert sticking out upstream of the Beaverdam dam.
climate_notes: Large flow events would likely overwhelm the culvert but there is multiple access points to the community so it could be repaired without significant issues.
priority_notes: Although there is a fiss sample site downstream there is no fisheries information for the system. However, because it is so close to the Kitwanga River fish presentce downstream is likely.
